1279","1180–Male":"1180–Overleden","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1154–1250":"1154–1250","about 1250":"circa 1250","ABT    1200":"circa 1200","about 1180":"circa 1180","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","ABT 1175":"circa 1175","Abt 1179":"circa 1179","1279":"1279","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1277":"1277","1145":"1145","1177":"1177","about 1154":"circa 1154","about 1177":"circa 1177","of Glyn Llifon,Llandwrog,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Llandwrog, Caernarfonshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales","of Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Radyr, Glamorgan, Wales":"Radyr, Glamorgan, Wales"},"en":{"about 1154–about 1250":"about 1154–about 1250","1145–Male":"1145–Deceased","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1177–1277":"1177–1277","1179–1279":"1179–1279","1180–Male":"1180–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1154–1250":"1154–1250","about 1250":"about 1250","ABT    1200":"about 1200","about 1180":"about 1180","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","ABT 1175":"about 1175","Abt 1179":"about 1179","1279":"1279","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1277":"1277","1145":"1145","1177":"1177","about 1154":"about 1154","about 1177":"about 1177","of Glyn Llifon,Llandwrog,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Llandwrog, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales","of Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Radyr, Glamorgan, Wales":"Radyr, Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Grufford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Rufford (Lancs, Notts), or Rufforth (WR Yorks).","2  English: perhaps a variant of   Ruffett   (1) or (2), altered by folk etymology to conform with the name in (1). Compare Thos. Ruffehead, 1722, Thos. Rufford, 1726 in   IGI   (Luton, Beds); Sara Ruffott, 1602, Sarah Rufford, 1627, Elizabeth Ruffoot, 1636, Mary Rowford, 1637 in   IGI   (Canterbury, Kent); William Rufford, 1749, William Ruffet, 1759, Mary Ruffett, 1763 in   IGI   (Strood, Kent). However, it is possible that Rufford in (1) migrated to the S Midlands and E Anglia, where it became confused with  <i>Ruffett</i> of other origins."],"variants":[{"name":"Ruffett","meanings":["1  English: variant of   Roughead  .","2  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>rugh(e)</i>,  <i>rogh(e)</i> ‘rough, hairy’ +  <i>fot</i> ‘foot’, the exact significance of which is obscure. Later forms of the name have probably been confused with (1) or (3).","3  English: locative name, variant of   Rufford  , though it is equally possible that modern instances of  <i>Rufford</i> are sometimes hypercorrections of  <i>Ruffit</i>, especially the name in (2)."]},{"name":"Roughead","meanings":["English, Scottish: nickname from Middle English and Older Scots  <i>rugh(e)</i>,  <i>ruf(e)</i>,  <i>ro(u)gh(e)</i> <i>ru(we)</i>,  <i>rowe</i> ‘rough, hairy’ +  <i>heved</i>,  <i>hed</i> ‘head’, for someone with shaggy or unkempt hair."]},{"name":"IGI","meanings":["English: perhaps an altered form of   Pritchett   or   Pritchard  . Compare Katherine Pratchett, 1654, Janam Pritchett, 1675 in   IGI   (Acton by Nantwich, Cheshire); Gulielmus Pritchard, 1675, Mary Pratchett, 1698 in   IGI   (Hatfield, Herts)."]}]},{"name":"Mawd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mawd verch Grufford was born about 1154, in Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales. She had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Hywel \"Goch\" ap Llywelyn. She died about 1250, in her hometown, at the age of 98, and was buried in Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales."},"et":{"about 1154–about 1250":"umbes 1154–umbes 1250","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1177–1277":"1177–1277","1179–1279":"1179–1279","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1154–1250":"1154–1250","about 1250":"umbes 1250","ABT    1200":"umbes 1200","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","ABT 1175":"umbes 1175","Abt 1179":"umbes 1179","1279":"1279","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1277":"1277","1145":"1145","1177":"1177","about 1154":"umbes 1154","about 1177":"umbes 1177","of Glyn Llifon,Llandwrog,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Llandwrog, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llantrithyd, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llantrith